back up the pipes,

31:27.174 --> 31:29.674
back up the hill.
where everybody else lives.

31:29.676 --> 31:32.677
That pump is called
a positive shit machine.

31:32.679 --> 31:34.346
- Really?
- Yeah. You following?

31:34.348 --> 31:35.779
Yeah. Not complicated.

31:35.781 --> 31:37.148
So, the sun is rising,

31:37.150 --> 31:39.951
we're covering great ground,
we're digging,

31:39.953 --> 31:41.786
- and then suddenly...
- What?

31:41.788 --> 31:42.787
Boom!

31:42.789 --> 31:45.223
A fucking earthquake!

31:45.225 --> 31:47.326
And, suddenly, there's a smell

31:47.328 --> 31:49.295
like we just
entered Dante's hell.

31:49.297 --> 31:52.696
And it's the pressurized
doo-doo in the tubes busted.

31:52.698 --> 31:54.865
- Oh, God!
- And it's fucking gushing!

31:54.867 --> 31:56.433
It's coming out like oil

31:56.435 --> 31:58.669
from the earth's
asshole non-stop.

31:58.671 --> 32:01.139
Five inches of
pure fucking shit!

32:01.141 --> 32:02.439
That's disgusting.

32:02.441 --> 32:04.376
And the central pump
feels the pressure,

32:04.378 --> 32:06.944
so it thinks it needs to keep
pushing harder and harder.

32:06.946 --> 32:08.412
Why didn't you turn it off?

32:08.414 --> 32:10.714
Can't turn it off. Only municipal
has access to the water system,

32:10.716 --> 32:12.416
and it's 5:00 a.m.,
and nobody's home.

32:12.418 --> 32:14.418
So, I'm looking at
this gated community

32:14.420 --> 32:16.855
literally drowning
in its own shit.

32:16.857 --> 32:19.590
The gatekeeper comes over.
He's got a few missing teeth.

32:19.592 --> 32:23.093
This old man puts his hand
on my shoulder, and he says:

32:23.095 --> 32:27.564
"You know, Mark, I've worked
for rich folks my whole life,

32:27.566 --> 32:31.769
"but deep down, I always knew
they were full of shit!"

32:31.771 --> 32:34.039
That's funny.

32:34.041 --> 32:34.738
Positive shit.

32:34.740 --> 32:36.341
Also, that was a long story.

32:43.015 --> 32:44.848
All right, guys.
I'll see ya later.

32:44.850 --> 32:46.719
- I'll see you in a bit! Bye!
- Yeah.

32:50.424 --> 32:52.424
Hey! Look at this!

32:52.426 --> 32:55.092
The, uh, presidential suite!

32:55.094 --> 32:56.794
Look, they
delivered your gear.

32:56.796 --> 32:58.295
Isn't that nice?

32:58.297 --> 33:01.432
And you got a desk there to
do your, uh, your coding.

33:01.434 --> 33:03.567
And...

33:03.569 --> 33:05.803
Look at that view!
Wow! That's incredible!

33:05.805 --> 33:08.839
So you can contemplate nature
while you do your coding.

33:08.841 --> 33:10.307
There's 3 phones.

33:10.309 --> 33:12.443
All right, well,
I will see you at dinner.

33:12.445 --> 33:13.543
Take your key.

33:13.545 --> 33:15.279
And please work on
that millisecond.

33:15.281 --> 33:17.281
All right, brother?
I know you can do it.

33:17.283 --> 33:18.581
- Yeah.
- OK!

33:49.382 --> 33:51.681
I think I found
something for the mountain.

33:51.683 --> 33:52.715
What'd you find?

33:52.717 --> 33:54.584
A friend of mine who
owns a couple of choppers

33:54.586 --> 33:58.287
says we can strap a drilling rig
to a Sikorsky S-61 helicopter.

33:58.289 --> 34:00.156
A Sikorsky helicopter?
What is that?

34:00.158 --> 34:02.525
That's basically a gigantic
motherfucking helicopter.

34:02.527 --> 34:04.627
It can lift up
to 20,000 pounds.

34:04.629 --> 34:05.628
Oh!

34:05.630 --> 34:07.331
The only thing
is we still need

34:07.333 --> 34:08.965
to get air-traffic
authorization

34:08.967 --> 34:11.137
to land it at the bottom
of the mountains.

34:19.944 --> 34:21.944
That's the thing.
It's $80,000 a day.

34:21.946 --> 34:23.679
A day?

34:23.681 --> 34:26.483
Yes. That includes
fuel and flight time.

34:26.485 --> 34:28.618
Fuck! Wow! Ooh!

34:28.620 --> 34:30.886
- What's wrong?
- No, nothing.

34:30.888 --> 34:32.922
I think they gave me
yesterday's fish.

34:32.924 --> 34:34.656
Two more things, Vinnie.

34:34.658 --> 34:36.324
We need air-traffic
authorization

34:36.327 --> 34:38.460
to land it at the
bottom of the mountain,

34:38.463 --> 34:40.464
and we still haven't
figured a way

34:40.466 --> 34:42.266
to land it
around here somewhere.

34:44.636 --> 34:46.101
What?

34:46.103 --> 34:49.237
Not "around here," OK?
Not "around here."

34:49.239 --> 34:51.474
Not around here.
Not around here.

34:51.476 --> 34:53.842
Not around here.
Not in Washika.

34:53.844 --> 34:56.646
We gotta be precise, all right?
Here, on the line.

34:56.648 --> 35:00.149
I mean, it looks like they're
building a straight fiber line

35:00.151 --> 35:02.651
between KAX and
the New York Stock Exchange.

35:02.653 --> 35:05.987
I know, Jenny.
I am looking at it.

35:05.989 --> 35:10.059
And I can't believe
I didn't see it coming,

35:10.061 --> 35:12.964
I mean, it was right there
in front of my face!

35:20.737 --> 35:23.171
I need you to make
the microwave towers work.

35:23.173 --> 35:25.774
Get me the pulse-shaping
algorithms yesterday.

35:25.776 --> 35:28.044
I already told you we can't.

35:28.046 --> 35:29.744
Oh yes, we can.

35:29.746 --> 35:32.782
We're gonna do a round trip,
Kansas-New York City,

35:32.784 --> 35:34.483
in 15 milliseconds or less.

35:34.485 --> 35:37.085
Eva, I just don't see
how you want us to do this.

35:37.087 --> 35:39.955
Give me the pulse shaping
or give me your resignation.

35:39.957 --> 35:41.890
Jenny, start looking
for other quants.

35:41.892 --> 35:45.228
I am going to start building
those towers tomorrow!

35:45.230 --> 35:47.263
- How are you?
- Good! How are you?

35:47.265 --> 35:48.697
- Welcome!
- Thank you so much!

35:48.699 --> 35:50.764
- So nice to have you.
- Nice to meet you.

35:50.766 --> 35:53.201
This is Ophelia Troller.
Vincent Zaleski.

35:53.203 --> 35:54.536
- Hi!
- Hi, Mr. Zaleski.

35:54.538 --> 35:56.638
Vincent, please.
Nice to meet you.

35:56.640 --> 35:58.508
Here's what
you need to know for now.

35:58.510 --> 36:00.142
We're digging a fiber tunnel
in this area.

36:00.144 --> 36:01.577
There's a long stretch of land

36:01.579 --> 36:03.579
that's protected
by National Parks.

36:03.581 --> 36:05.046
We heard that
you're the best,

36:05.048 --> 36:07.048
and we're looking
for someone to drill

36:07.050 --> 36:09.384
under that land
in one single stretch.

36:09.386 --> 36:12.354
OK, we're talking about,
like, 15 miles.

36:12.356 --> 36:16.258
So, you guys want 15 miles of
horizontal drilling in one go?

36:16.260 --> 36:19.261
- Mm-hmm.
- Why no connection points?

36:19.263 --> 36:22.196
It's all protected wild
forest. There's no access roads.

36:22.198 --> 36:25.133
There's no way to get
permission to build one.

36:25.135 --> 36:26.934
You have any idea
what kind of machine

36:26.936 --> 36:29.037
it takes to do
this kind of a job?

36:29.039 --> 36:31.606
I'm talking shipped from
the other side of the planet.

36:31.608 --> 36:33.508
So that's hundreds of
thousands of dollars

36:33.510 --> 36:34.609
just to get that machine here.

36:34.611 --> 36:37.145
- Exactly.
- Yeah.

36:38.814 --> 36:40.082
Yeah, good to go.

37:13.849 --> 37:15.449
<i>Hello?</i>

37:15.451 --> 37:17.686
Hi, it's me.
Yeah, my stomach is killing me.

37:17.688 --> 37:19.621
Uh, I think I need
to see a doctor.

37:19.623 --> 37:20.622
<i>What's wrong?</i>

37:20.624 --> 37:22.189
Probably just something I ate.

37:22.191 --> 37:23.258
<i>Meet me downstairs.</i>

37:23.260 --> 37:24.526
Yeah, thanks.
Oh, Mark?

37:24.528 --> 37:25.992
<i>Yeah?</i>

37:25.994 --> 37:27.294
Don't tell Anton.

37:27.296 --> 37:28.631
<i>Sure.</i>

38:21.116 --> 38:22.483
<i>Mr. Zaleski.</i>

38:22.485 --> 38:23.484
<i>Yes?</i>

38:23.486 --> 38:26.222
There's no easy way
to say this.

38:28.691 --> 38:30.225
Say what?

38:38.401 --> 38:39.700
Hey!

38:39.702 --> 38:41.468
Yo! What they say?

38:41.470 --> 38:42.869
Oh, nothing! I'm good!

38:42.871 --> 38:45.339
They kept you in there
for 6 hours for nothing?

38:45.341 --> 38:46.539
What, are they stupid?

38:46.541 --> 38:47.874
I know, sorry.

38:47.876 --> 38:50.443
They just had to run
some tests, but I'm good.

38:50.445 --> 38:53.346
Are you sure, man?
You still look a little pale.

38:53.348 --> 38:55.250
Yeah, I'm good!
Come on, let's go.

39:01.557 --> 39:03.891
You have stomach cancer.

39:06.094 --> 39:10.365
You have to undergo treatment
immediately. I'm sorry.

39:13.201 --> 39:14.768
Can I get a second opinion?

39:14.770 --> 39:18.003
You can, but with the X-rays
and the endoscopy and the MRI,

39:18.005 --> 39:20.074
it's pretty clear.

39:21.075 --> 39:23.078
I'm really sorry.

39:27.215 --> 39:30.383
Is that why I've been
having these nightmares?

39:30.385 --> 39:32.185
Nightmares?

39:32.187 --> 39:35.020
Yes, I've been having these
very strange nightmares.

39:35.022 --> 39:36.456
Is it because of the cancer?

39:36.458 --> 39:37.490
I don't know.

39:37.492 --> 39:39.625
This old man is chasing me.

39:39.627 --> 39:41.194
I don't think it's related.

39:41.196 --> 39:43.029
I don't know if
he's trying to kill me

39:43.031 --> 39:45.064
or if he's trying
to save me from something.

39:45.066 --> 39:47.700
Mr. Zaleski, please.
I'm not a psychiatrist.

39:47.702 --> 39:48.802
It's related, isn't it?

39:48.804 --> 39:51.203
<i>I'm sorry,
I can't help you.</i>

39:51.205 --> 39:52.973
<i>I don't have the training.</i>

39:54.743 --> 39:56.108
<i>How long do I have?</i>

39:56.110 --> 39:58.311
<i>You can live
a mostly productive life</i>

39:58.313 --> 39:59.712
<i>for the next year or two,</i>

39:59.714 --> 40:02.315
<i>like 90% of our patients
under your condition.</i>

40:02.317 --> 40:03.915
And then what?

40:03.917 --> 40:07.319
<i>One out of two patients
with your level of advancement</i>

40:07.321 --> 40:08.788
<i>live beyond 5 years.</i>

40:08.790 --> 40:11.123
<i>It's not a death sentence,</i>

40:11.125 --> 40:13.392
<i>but it's very serious.</i>

40:13.394 --> 40:15.360
<i>And with the right treatment,</i>

40:15.362 --> 40:18.930
<i>you could be 100% cured
in a couple of years.</i>

40:21.068 --> 40:24.569
Is there any way the treatment
can wait for a couple months?

40:24.571 --> 40:27.406
I'm just in the middle
of something very important.

40:27.408 --> 40:29.441
A lot of people
are counting on me,

40:29.443 --> 40:31.109
and I just can't fail them.

40:31.111 --> 40:32.612
No, it can't.

40:32.614 --> 40:35.082
It would seriously
put your life at risk.

41:36.209 --> 41:38.108
All right,
this one is yours.

41:38.110 --> 41:40.145
- Thank you so much.
- Thank you.

41:40.147 --> 41:43.483
It's great to meet you,
and we'll be in touch, OK?

42:18.818 --> 42:21.955
<i>You OK? I mean,
we haven't heard from you.</i>

42:23.322 --> 42:25.055
<i>Yeah, I'm fine.</i>

42:25.057 --> 42:26.290
<i>A little tired.</i>

42:26.292 --> 42:28.994
- <i>Well, how's work?</i>
- It's all right.

42:28.996 --> 42:31.495
<i>Look, I hope you're not
just eating crap out there.</i>

42:31.497 --> 42:33.766
You're gonna end up
with diabetes.

42:38.905 --> 42:39.904
Anton.

42:39.906 --> 42:41.006
<i>No, I'm not.</i>

42:42.275 --> 42:44.475
Here talk to your daughter.
She misses you.

42:44.477 --> 42:45.976
Katia!

42:45.978 --> 42:47.043
Who is it?

42:47.045 --> 42:48.044
It's your father.

42:48.046 --> 42:49.880
Hi, Dad!

42:49.882 --> 42:51.047
Hi, Katia.

42:51.049 --> 42:52.550
<i>What are you doing?</i>

42:52.552 --> 42:53.851
Ah, just working.

42:53.853 --> 42:56.152
<i>OK, I got a new book.
It's about atoms.</i>

42:56.154 --> 42:57.454
Yeah?

42:57.456 --> 42:59.189
Do you know how
much empty space

42:59.191 --> 43:00.658
there is in
a hydrogen atom?

43:00.660 --> 43:01.791
How many?

43:01.793 --> 43:02.993
Tell me.

43:02.995 --> 43:05.228
<i>99.99996%.</i>

43:05.230 --> 43:07.831
If the atom were the size
of the Empire State Building,

43:07.833 --> 43:11.167
the proton and its centre would
be about the size of a bee.

43:11.169 --> 43:13.102
All the rest is emptiness!

43:13.104 --> 43:14.605
<i>Pretty crazy, huh?</i>

43:14.607 --> 43:16.509
Yeah, that's pretty crazy.

43:41.633 --> 43:42.632
What's up, Ray?

43:42.634 --> 43:43.934
Good. How you doing?

43:43.936 --> 43:45.368
- Good.
- All right!

43:45.370 --> 43:46.704
You know Vincent?

43:46.706 --> 43:47.838
Hi! How are you?

43:47.840 --> 43:49.539
Mr. Zaleski!
Good, thank you. Here!

43:49.541 --> 43:51.139
Where are the cliffs?

43:51.141 --> 43:52.709
Uh, that way.

43:52.711 --> 43:54.243
Please put these on.

43:54.245 --> 43:56.579
Why do we need
such a straight line?

43:56.581 --> 43:58.314
Why can't we go
around the mountain?

43:58.316 --> 44:00.750
Come on, Ray, no questions.
It's in your contract.

44:00.752 --> 44:02.820
Contract!
What's a contract around here?

44:02.822 --> 44:04.991
Just a piece of paper
to wipe your ass with.

44:14.332 --> 44:16.132
Hello, Anton.

44:16.134 --> 44:17.900
What are you doing here?

44:17.902 --> 44:20.203
You probably think
I came here to remind you

44:20.205 --> 44:21.703
that you cannot
use my codes.

44:21.705 --> 44:24.272
Pfft! Well, I don't care
about the codes.

44:24.274 --> 44:25.875
Of course you don't.

44:25.877 --> 44:26.943
They're archaic.

44:26.945 --> 44:28.645
Hmm!

44:28.647 --> 44:33.148
Well, I just came here
to tell you a story.

44:33.150 --> 44:36.319
Have you heard
of Vladimir Smirnov?

44:36.321 --> 44:37.886
No.

44:37.888 --> 44:41.556
He rewrote some code for
the McMinster Fund 8 years ago.

44:41.558 --> 44:44.259
He gave them a 10- or
12-millisecond edge

44:44.261 --> 44:45.527
on the network.

44:45.529 --> 44:47.597
One day, he decided
to leave the firm,

44:47.599 --> 44:50.833
and he took a couple of
lines of code with him.

44:50.835 --> 44:53.702
Nothing special,
just generic code.

44:53.704 --> 44:55.871
But McMinster
didn't like it.

44:55.873 --> 44:58.740
So they threw
the FBI on Smirnov.

44:58.742 --> 45:02.377
They claimed that he was a
threat to national security,

45:02.379 --> 45:04.847
that he had stolen
some codes from them,

45:04.849 --> 45:08.820
that he was capable
of crashing the markets.

45:10.421 --> 45:12.856
He has been in jail
for the last 8 years.

45:19.998 --> 45:22.364
Vladimir didn't do
anything wrong.

45:22.366 --> 45:24.499
But it just goes to show you

45:24.501 --> 45:28.271
that someone can make your life
hell if they decide to.

45:30.140 --> 45:33.842
How old will your daughters
be in 8 years, Anton?

45:34.845 --> 45:37.347
Eight years is
a long time.

45:43.921 --> 45:48.357
I cared for you,
and you betrayed me.

45:49.693 --> 45:51.727
Now you have to pay,

45:51.729 --> 45:54.262
and I'm gonna make it painful.

46:58.061 --> 46:59.693
Yeah?

46:59.695 --> 47:01.594
Whoa, whoa!
Hey, hey! Stop the car!

47:01.596 --> 47:03.931
Yeah, let me
call you back.

47:03.933 --> 47:05.499
Fuck! Hey! Hey!

47:05.501 --> 47:07.735
Come back here, you bitch!

47:07.737 --> 47:11.772
Yeah, you!
Hey! Asshole!

47:11.774 --> 47:14.375
Oh, you think
you have power over us?

47:14.377 --> 47:16.178
Oh, you think you own us?

47:16.180 --> 47:19.412
Hey, come down,
you piece of shit!

47:19.414 --> 47:21.050
What the fuck?

47:23.853 --> 47:25.418
What is she doing here?

47:25.420 --> 47:26.654
Hey!

47:26.656 --> 47:27.755
Hey, you OK?

47:27.757 --> 47:28.989
Yeah.

47:28.991 --> 47:31.559
I just saw Torres'
helicopter fly out here.

47:31.561 --> 47:34.494
- Oh, really?
- Yeah, really. Did you see her?

47:34.496 --> 47:36.130
Hey, look at me!
Did you see her?

47:36.132 --> 47:37.865
- Hey!
- Yeah, yeah, I saw her.

47:37.867 --> 47:39.200
You saw her?

47:39.202 --> 47:40.868
- Yeah, I just, I didn't...
- What?

47:40.870 --> 47:43.369
I didn't tell you 'cause
I didn't wanna upset you.

47:43.371 --> 47:45.639
You're not upsetting me.
What did she say to you?

47:45.641 --> 47:46.574
Nah, just some...

47:46.576 --> 47:47.908
What did she say to you?

47:47.910 --> 47:49.310
Just some stupid story.

47:49.312 --> 47:51.778
Some story? OK, look at me.
Did she threaten you?

47:51.780 --> 47:53.280
I'm not scared of her.

47:53.282 --> 47:55.082
- You don't have to be.
- No.

47:55.084 --> 47:56.749
She didn't lay
a hand on you?

47:56.751 --> 47:57.918
- Did she?
- No.

47:57.920 --> 47:59.920
Did she tell you
what she was doing?

47:59.922 --> 48:02.022
Hey! OK, just look
at me when I'm...

48:02.024 --> 48:03.389
What did she say to you?

48:03.391 --> 48:04.424
- Stop! Stop!
- OK.

48:04.426 --> 48:06.192
I'm doing everything I can

48:06.194 --> 48:07.360
to find that millisecond,

48:07.362 --> 48:09.095
so stop interrupting me!

48:09.097 --> 48:10.129
I can't focus!

48:10.131 --> 48:11.131
OK.

48:11.133 --> 48:12.899
- I can't think!
- OK, I'm not...

48:12.901 --> 48:14.237
OK?

48:15.537 --> 48:16.937
- Leave me alone!
- OK.

48:16.939 --> 48:18.072
Leave me alone!

48:18.074 --> 48:19.073
OK, OK!

48:19.075 --> 48:20.241
Get out of here!

48:20.243 --> 48:21.506
All right, all right!

48:21.508 --> 48:22.575
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

48:36.325 --> 48:38.057
There it is,
right on schedule,

48:38.059 --> 48:40.260
the first of
your 34 towers.

48:40.262 --> 48:44.497
Kansas Electronic Exchange,
New York Stock Exchange.

48:44.499 --> 48:47.000
18 towers that way,
15 towers that way.

48:47.002 --> 48:48.201
Where are they digging?

48:48.203 --> 48:49.736
Vinnie and Anton's
guys are

48:49.738 --> 48:51.105
right at the bottom
of that cliff.

48:51.107 --> 48:52.906
That little patch
with less trees there

48:52.908 --> 48:54.539
in the forest
facing the cliff,

48:54.541 --> 48:55.741
that's the digging.

48:55.743 --> 48:58.610
They have over 50 crews,
12 in Pennsylvania.

48:58.612 --> 48:59.979
Shit!

48:59.981 --> 49:02.083
Get me back to New York.

49:06.922 --> 49:08.289
What the hell?

49:08.291 --> 49:10.889
What are they doing?
They... They're packing up!

49:10.891 --> 49:12.891
Wait! Stop the car.
Stop the car!

49:12.893 --> 49:14.193
Hey! Hey! Hey! Yo!

49:14.195 --> 49:16.996
Hey! What... what do
you think you're doing?

49:16.998 --> 49:18.331
We're leaving.

49:18.333 --> 49:20.667
You can't do that.
That's a breach of contract!

49:20.669 --> 49:22.869
Of course we can.
It's expensive, but we can!

49:22.871 --> 49:24.570
We owe you $30,000.
You get a check by Monday.

49:24.572 --> 49:26.238
- Excuse me.
- Why are you doing this?

49:26.240 --> 49:28.807
We got a better contract.
More pay for much less work.

49:28.809 --> 49:30.075
So, you're just leaving?

49:30.077 --> 49:31.543
Look, I got bills
to pay, OK?

49:31.545 --> 49:32.711
He has bills to pay!

49:32.713 --> 49:34.546
It's just business.
Nothing personal.

49:34.548 --> 49:36.416
Who gave you the
contract? Who was it?

49:36.418 --> 49:38.685
I signed a
non-disclosure agreement.

49:38.687 --> 49:41.153
It's Eva Torres, isn't it?
It's Eva Torres, say it!

49:41.155 --> 49:43.221
If you told her anything
about our project...

49:43.223 --> 49:44.222
Vinnie, calm down!

49:44.224 --> 49:45.857
...I will personally
fuck you up!

49:45.859 --> 49:48.227
- Careful what you wish for!
- OK! Fuck you!

49:48.229 --> 49:49.828
Have I ever mistreated you?

49:49.830 --> 49:52.864
I paid you to the moon and back!
Why the fuck are you doing this?

49:52.866 --> 49:55.001
You think she's trying
to build her own line?

49:55.003 --> 49:56.735
No, we're way too ahead
of the game for them.

49:56.737 --> 49:59.805
They're trying to screw us.

49:59.807 --> 50:01.673
What do you want me
to do with his contract?

50:01.675 --> 50:03.642
Give this contract
to somebody else,

50:03.644 --> 50:05.510
and figure out if they
stole any more of our crews.

50:05.512 --> 50:07.213
Listen to me, double
their wages if you have to,

50:07.215 --> 50:08.247
but keep them working!

50:08.249 --> 50:09.282
All right.

50:16.824 --> 50:18.325
Thank you.

50:20.294 --> 50:22.129
What are you
working on?

50:23.364 --> 50:25.831
Oh, I can't really
talk about it.

50:25.833 --> 50:27.233
Mm-hmm.

50:27.235 --> 50:30.070
Is that 'cause you're a spy
who works for the CIA?

50:31.038 --> 50:32.870
No.

50:32.872 --> 50:36.674
No, it's because Vincent says
everyone has to sign an NDA.

50:36.676 --> 50:38.310
So I can't talk about it.

50:38.312 --> 50:40.312
Hmm! Who's Vincent?

50:40.314 --> 50:43.416
Is that your boss at the CIA,
because you're a spy?

50:43.418 --> 50:44.949
I don't work for the CIA.

50:44.951 --> 50:48.286
Yeah, right! I have some
friends in the KGB.

50:48.288 --> 50:51.358
I'll go back there, call them,
tell 'em you're here.

50:52.658 --> 50:54.192
That's ridiculous!

50:54.194 --> 50:56.161
Come on, tell me!

50:56.163 --> 50:57.731
Please?

51:02.403 --> 51:03.801
Do you have a pen?

51:03.803 --> 51:05.404
"I, Barbara Lehman,

51:05.406 --> 51:08.340
"swear not to divulge
any information

51:08.342 --> 51:12.377
"related to Anton Zaleski's
professional activities."

51:14.014 --> 51:17.281
You know this is never gonna
hold up in court, right?

51:17.283 --> 51:18.484
Oh, it will.

51:21.220 --> 51:24.322
Well, I'm here to make digital
information travel faster

51:24.324 --> 51:26.324
between the Kansas
Electronic Exchange

51:26.326 --> 51:28.093
and the New York
Stock Exchange.

51:28.095 --> 51:29.627
OK.

51:29.629 --> 51:32.431
Let's say you're
an investor in Kansas,

51:32.433 --> 51:34.631
and I'm a trader
also in Kansas,

51:34.633 --> 51:36.467
and you wanna buy...

51:36.469 --> 51:39.637
Uh, I don't know,
what do you wanna buy?

51:39.639 --> 51:41.972
Um, what do I wanna buy?

51:41.974 --> 51:45.678
I would like to buy...

51:47.214 --> 51:49.146
a lemon company in, um,

51:49.148 --> 51:51.015
I don't know,
Zimbabwe.

51:51.017 --> 51:54.418
So you wanna buy shares
in a lemon company in Zimbabwe.

51:54.420 --> 51:56.053
Right.

51:56.055 --> 51:58.089
Let's say you wanna
buy 1,000 shares

51:58.091 --> 51:58.923
at a maximum
price of $10.

51:58.925 --> 52:00.257
All right,
let's do that.

52:00.259 --> 52:02.860
OK, so you put this
request in the system,

52:02.862 --> 52:05.995
and a bunch of traders can
now offer selling prices

52:05.997 --> 52:07.997
for the lemon
company in Zimbabwe.

52:07.999 --> 52:10.534
But the thing is, if all
traders use the same system

52:10.536 --> 52:12.036
and have the
same information,

52:12.038 --> 52:13.370
how do you beat the others?

52:13.372 --> 52:15.139
By having the fastest line.

52:15.141 --> 52:17.975
Once I know how much
you're willing to pay,

52:17.977 --> 52:20.811
I outrun the other traders
from Kansas to New York.

52:20.813 --> 52:23.380
I buy shares that sell
for less than $10.

52:23.382 --> 52:26.183
I race back and sell them
to you for $10.

52:26.185 --> 52:28.319
So, right now,
all this happens

52:28.321 --> 52:31.388
in about in about
17 milliseconds.

52:31.390 --> 52:32.990
Soon it'll be 16.

52:32.992 --> 52:36.360
But what's
16 milliseconds?

52:36.362 --> 52:39.129
It's one single flap
of a hummingbird's wing.

52:39.131 --> 52:41.731
OK, but then what happens?

52:41.733 --> 52:44.502
Well, that's it.
That's the whole thing.

52:44.504 --> 52:48.572
I've just made 1,000 times
one cent, so I've made 10 bucks.

52:48.574 --> 52:50.908
You're doing all of
this for 10 bucks?

52:50.910 --> 52:53.576
Well, I do 200,000
transactions like this

52:53.578 --> 52:54.577
every day.

52:54.579 --> 52:56.846
That's 200,000 times
$10 times 252.

52:56.848 --> 52:59.082
That's roughly
$500 million a year.

52:59.084 --> 53:01.284
That's a lot of money.

53:01.286 --> 53:02.685
It's like time travel.

53:02.687 --> 53:03.855
Yeah!

53:04.890 --> 53:06.723
But what about the farmers?

53:06.725 --> 53:09.259
What about' em?

53:09.261 --> 53:11.995
The lemon farmers in Zimbabwe,
what do they get out of this?

53:11.997 --> 53:13.630
The lemon farmers
aren't relevant.

53:13.632 --> 53:16.432
How can they be irrelevant?
They're growing the lemons.

53:16.434 --> 53:18.768
They're not an important
variable in the system.

53:18.770 --> 53:21.472
Mathematically, for our business
plan, they're irrelevant.

53:21.474 --> 53:24.542
I guess I wouldn't wanna be
one of those farmers in Zimbabwe

53:24.544 --> 53:27.110
who's mathematically irrelevant
to your business plan.

53:28.746 --> 53:29.878
OK, I'm sorry.

53:29.880 --> 53:32.582
I'll shut up and
I'll get back to work.

53:32.584 --> 53:34.284
No, no, no. It's...

53:34.286 --> 53:36.587
It's an interesting problem.

53:36.589 --> 53:40.223
It raises a lot of
epistemological questions.

53:40.225 --> 53:42.260
See ya, spy!

53:59.310 --> 54:00.909
What is it?

54:00.911 --> 54:02.110
It's a thesis.

54:02.112 --> 54:03.845
23-year-old kid out of NYU.

54:03.847 --> 54:05.983
I think he figured out
the pulse shaping.

54:06.984 --> 54:09.152
You did this?

54:09.154 --> 54:10.954
Uh, yeah, I guess.

54:10.956 --> 54:12.622
You can make the pulsing work?

54:12.624 --> 54:14.356
Yeah, I mean,
it's theoretical,

54:14.358 --> 54:16.827
but, yeah, I don't see
why it wouldn't work.

54:19.497 --> 54:21.065
Follow me.

54:22.066 --> 54:24.469
<i>I knew you were out there.</i>

54:25.836 --> 54:28.671
You know when you
get this sensation

54:28.673 --> 54:32.474
that there is someone that is
supposed to be in your life,

54:32.476 --> 54:35.312
but they just can't quite
find their way in?

54:36.447 --> 54:38.947
What did you think
about Jenny?

54:38.949 --> 54:41.149
She's all right, I guess.

54:41.151 --> 54:42.552
She's brilliant.

54:42.554 --> 54:45.753
They all are.
I only hire the best.

54:45.755 --> 54:49.524
I think you're gonna
feel at home with us.

54:49.526 --> 54:52.894
I'm gonna start you
at $150 000 a year.

54:52.896 --> 54:54.162
Is it all right?

54:54.164 --> 54:55.565
Thank you!

54:55.567 --> 54:58.434
I mean, this seems like a really
stimulating environment

54:58.436 --> 54:59.768
to be working in...

54:59.770 --> 55:02.471
However, if you can
make the pulse shaping work

55:02.473 --> 55:04.839
for our towers before
the end of the month,

55:04.841 --> 55:06.975
I'm gonna give you
a bonus of $300,000.

55:06.977 --> 55:09.845
I'm going to take
such good care of you

55:09.847 --> 55:13.384
as long as you prove
to be who I think you are.

55:15.019 --> 55:17.353
And as long as you're loyal.

55:23.193 --> 55:25.527
OK, so this is the area.

55:25.529 --> 55:26.962
Now, you, of course, wanna get

55:26.964 --> 55:29.298
the biggest, most expensive
digger on the planet.

55:29.300 --> 55:32.367
You want to dig along the forest
and then under the river, right?

55:32.369 --> 55:33.367
Uh-huh.

55:33.369 --> 55:35.036
You said they'd
never let you dig

55:35.038 --> 55:36.505
an access road through
the National Park.

55:36.507 --> 55:37.673
Probably right,
but you're thinking

55:37.675 --> 55:39.441
this is the only way
to get there.

55:39.443 --> 55:41.543
- Yeah, it is.
- No, it's not.

55:41.545 --> 55:44.112
Look, you have
9 little rivers here.

55:44.114 --> 55:46.348
OK, if I give you
4 mini-diggers,

55:46.350 --> 55:48.649
I put them on rafts
and rack 'em along the rivers

55:48.651 --> 55:51.052
and have them all
working at the same time,

55:51.054 --> 55:53.487
pretty sure that,
for half your budget,

55:53.489 --> 55:55.990
I can get the job
done 4 times as fast.

55:55.992 --> 55:59.528
On the phone you said
twice as fast, not four times.

55:59.530 --> 56:02.633
Yeah, well,
you know, Murphy's law.

56:03.634 --> 56:05.168
I'm a pessimist.

56:09.172 --> 56:11.339
I wanna come on the raft.

56:11.341 --> 56:13.809
Well, I hope you brought
your winter jacket,

56:13.811 --> 56:16.112
'cause it just
snowed up there.

56:31.594 --> 56:34.261
Yeah, my father
would've liked it here.

56:34.263 --> 56:36.263
My parents were born in Russia.

56:36.265 --> 56:38.599
Yeah, they moved here
in the '60s,

56:38.601 --> 56:41.802
moved into a tiny apartment
with 10 other Russian families.

56:41.804 --> 56:43.337
Two weeks after he got here,

56:43.339 --> 56:45.473
these police came,
knocked on his door,

56:45.475 --> 56:47.375
threw him in
the back of the car,

56:47.377 --> 56:49.410
thought we was a spy,
which he wasn't.

56:49.412 --> 56:52.313
They interrogated him for,
like, 4 weeks or something.

56:52.315 --> 56:54.114
He never saw the
light of the day.

56:54.116 --> 56:55.649
- That's insane!
- Yeah!

56:55.651 --> 56:58.853
My mother said he became like
a totally different person.

56:58.855 --> 57:00.621
He became, like, angry.

57:00.623 --> 57:03.791
Yeah, and I was born a
few years later, so lucky!

57:03.793 --> 57:04.792
Yeah.

57:04.794 --> 57:06.560
He always told me
the same thing.

57:06.562 --> 57:07.995
He said:
"Whatever you do,

57:07.997 --> 57:10.563
"make sure you own
your freedom."

57:10.565 --> 57:12.165
Own your freedom?

57:12.167 --> 57:14.702
Doesn't that kind of defeat
the purpose of freedom?

57:14.704 --> 57:15.803
Yeah, maybe.

57:15.805 --> 57:18.104
And he was always trying to,

57:18.106 --> 57:22.278
like, scare me or something
into being, like...

57:23.513 --> 57:26.012
I don't know,
like, successful.

57:26.014 --> 57:29.786
So, you think you're doing
this to prove your father wrong?

57:31.286 --> 57:33.587
Wrong about what?

57:33.589 --> 57:35.155
About being
successful.

57:35.157 --> 57:38.428
It's a pretty crazy project
you got going here.

57:41.061 --> 57:45.133
It's just... it's just
something I need to do.

57:50.172 --> 57:51.707
We're here.

58:16.798 --> 58:18.298
That's incredible!

58:18.300 --> 58:20.333
- That's amazing!
- Yeah?

58:20.335 --> 58:22.302
- Yeah, thanks.
- Yeah, no problem.

58:22.304 --> 58:23.703
Listen, I have
a bunch of work

58:23.705 --> 58:25.472
that I still have
to finish up here,

58:25.474 --> 58:26.807
but Pete'll
take you back.

58:26.809 --> 58:28.574
He's waiting for you
on the other side.

58:28.576 --> 58:29.575
- OK.
- All right?

58:29.577 --> 58:30.577
Thank you.

58:30.579 --> 58:33.347
And, uh,
I hope you make it.

59:13.855 --> 59:15.288
No housekeeping!

59:21.161 --> 59:23.295
Anton!

59:23.297 --> 59:25.232
Anton, it's me.
Open up.

59:27.769 --> 59:28.835
Yo, Anton!

59:28.837 --> 59:29.869
Yeah, I'm coming.

59:29.871 --> 59:30.870
Hi!

59:30.872 --> 59:32.039
Hi! Thanks.

59:33.039 --> 59:34.339
Oh!

59:34.341 --> 59:35.641
All right,
so, good news.

59:35.643 --> 59:37.709
We got 600 miles of
the line completed,

59:37.711 --> 59:40.946
and the helicopter flies to
the cliffs today, which is good.

59:40.948 --> 59:41.948
How about you?

59:41.950 --> 59:44.951
How are you doing?
Where are we at?

59:44.953 --> 59:47.286
I only cut a 10th
of a millisecond off.

59:47.288 --> 59:49.788
A 10th of a millisecond,
that's not bad!

59:49.790 --> 59:51.790
That's a start!
It's a good start!

59:51.792 --> 59:53.190
Oh!

59:53.192 --> 59:56.295
You OK? Hey!

59:56.297 --> 59:58.832
Come on!
Dude, what's going on?

01:00:00.334 --> 01:00:02.801
Well, the system's
missing some variables.

01:00:02.803 --> 01:00:05.069
OK. Well, whatever it is,
we can fix it.

01:00:05.071 --> 01:00:06.504
We'll fix it.

01:00:06.506 --> 01:00:08.139
There's granularity issues.

01:00:08.141 --> 01:00:10.576
Well, what is that?
I don't know what that is.

01:00:10.578 --> 01:00:11.910
The lemon farmers.

01:00:11.912 --> 01:00:14.346
The core economic units
don't have enough resources.

01:00:14.348 --> 01:00:15.614
OK.

01:00:15.616 --> 01:00:18.317
It's all gonna collapse
in about 50 years,

01:00:18.319 --> 01:00:21.754
unless we get the algos
to factor in the lemons.

01:00:22.755 --> 01:00:24.488
OK, you know what?

01:00:24.490 --> 01:00:25.924
There's bugs
in the system.

01:00:25.926 --> 01:00:28.660
You and me are going on
a little road trip, all right?

01:00:28.662 --> 01:00:31.730
Gonna get your mind off coding
for a few hours or a few days.

01:00:31.732 --> 01:00:33.097
I gotta finish this.

01:00:33.099 --> 01:00:34.466
Hey! I'm not asking, buddy.

01:00:34.468 --> 01:00:36.168
Come on, let's go
see the helicopter!

01:00:36.170 --> 01:00:38.569
Change your clothes.
We'll get you some fresh air.

01:00:38.571 --> 01:00:39.570
Anton!

01:00:40.907 --> 01:00:43.107
Um, I have a question

01:00:43.109 --> 01:00:47.478
regarding a fiber connector,
model 2MMTR5547.

01:00:47.480 --> 01:00:49.380
<i>OK, what's the question?</i>

01:00:49.382 --> 01:00:51.483
Is the dissipation
index accurate,

01:00:51.485 --> 01:00:54.952
or could there be slight
variations in the speed loss?

01:00:54.954 --> 01:00:58.522
<i>No, sir, I don't think there
is anything significant there.</i>

01:00:58.524 --> 01:01:01.292
Is there any tolerance,
like even 0.1%?

01:01:01.294 --> 01:01:03.762
<i>The numbers you have
are in optimal conditions.</i>

01:01:03.764 --> 01:01:05.129
<i>If there was some difference,</i>

01:01:05.131 --> 01:01:06.765
<i>I'd say it was
the other way around.</i>

01:01:06.767 --> 01:01:09.066
<i>You might get slightly
less performance than that.</i>

01:01:09.068 --> 01:01:11.435
Well, that's pretty stupid.

01:01:11.437 --> 01:01:13.271
<i>Excuse me, sir?</i>

01:01:14.807 --> 01:01:17.408
Hey! Hey,
do you feel that?

01:01:17.410 --> 01:01:18.442
Flat tire.

01:01:18.444 --> 01:01:20.344
Shit! Are you serious?

01:01:20.346 --> 01:01:21.347
Yeah.

01:01:34.627 --> 01:01:35.826
An hour?

01:01:35.828 --> 01:01:38.464
All right, all right.
Just please hurry.

01:01:52.177 --> 01:01:53.713
Hey!

01:01:55.715 --> 01:01:57.347
You think when this is over,

01:01:57.349 --> 01:01:58.915
I could take your kids out,

01:01:58.917 --> 01:02:01.418
um, like, for
ice cream or something?

01:02:01.420 --> 01:02:03.520
Yeah, they'd really like that.

01:02:03.522 --> 01:02:04.521
Yeah?

01:02:04.523 --> 01:02:05.923
Yeah.

01:02:05.925 --> 01:02:08.161
I guess I would like to.

01:02:09.194 --> 01:02:11.263
Yeah, anytime.

01:02:26.179 --> 01:02:27.611
Vincent!

01:02:27.613 --> 01:02:28.611
Yeah.

01:02:28.613 --> 01:02:30.747
What is it?

01:02:30.749 --> 01:02:32.248
It's a frog.

01:02:32.250 --> 01:02:34.286
That's cute.
Yeah, it's good.

01:02:36.955 --> 01:02:38.655
OK. Oh!

01:02:38.657 --> 01:02:40.623
Go in the water.
There, that's better.

01:02:40.625 --> 01:02:41.624
It's OK?

01:02:41.626 --> 01:02:43.259
He's fine.
It's just a... Yeah.

01:02:43.261 --> 01:02:44.460
You know, pretty soon,

01:02:44.462 --> 01:02:47.063
when you got your
country home on the hill,

01:02:47.065 --> 01:02:50.133
you could just hang out and
do shit like this all the time.

01:02:51.503 --> 01:02:53.636
It's not really
about the home.

01:02:53.638 --> 01:02:56.040
It's about people
leaving me alone.

01:02:56.042 --> 01:02:57.607
Most people are morons.

01:02:57.609 --> 01:02:59.009
Yeah?

01:02:59.011 --> 01:03:01.144
I just wanna get
a place somewhere quiet,

01:03:01.146 --> 01:03:03.312
where I can work on my codes,

01:03:03.314 --> 01:03:04.848
type some algos...

01:03:04.850 --> 01:03:06.149
Mm-hmm.

01:03:06.151 --> 01:03:09.519
...hang out with
Masha and the girls and you.

01:03:09.521 --> 01:03:13.556
We can go swim in a lake
and watch the sunset.

01:03:13.558 --> 01:03:16.192
Whatever the people
do in the country.

01:03:19.630 --> 01:03:20.763
Not bad!

01:03:20.765 --> 01:03:21.765
That was three!

01:03:21.767 --> 01:03:23.332
Yeah. Oh!

01:03:23.334 --> 01:03:24.366
Ah!

01:03:24.368 --> 01:03:26.836
Hey! Yo, yo!

01:03:26.838 --> 01:03:28.471
Hey!

01:03:28.473 --> 01:03:29.973
All right, let's go.

01:03:34.712 --> 01:03:37.013
OK, guys, hurry!
Put these on!

01:03:37.015 --> 01:03:38.280
- Hey!
- How's it going?

01:03:38.282 --> 01:03:39.748
Sorry about that.

01:03:39.750 --> 01:03:41.184
No worries.
Put the helmet.

01:03:41.186 --> 01:03:43.019
Here, goggles first
and then helmet.

01:03:48.492 --> 01:03:50.027
Whoo!

01:03:51.095 --> 01:03:52.361
OK!

01:03:54.232 --> 01:03:55.633
Whoo!

01:03:56.667 --> 01:03:59.068
Holy shit!

01:04:03.809 --> 01:04:05.908
Stand clear for delivery.

01:04:05.910 --> 01:04:08.844
Stand back.
Watch out for that ledge.

01:04:12.383 --> 01:04:13.682
Whoo!

01:04:15.686 --> 01:04:17.020
Hold on!

01:04:20.025 --> 01:04:22.456
Good, good!
All right, all right!

01:04:27.698 --> 01:04:29.031
Keep it coming!

01:04:39.709 --> 01:04:41.210
Back it up, back it up!

01:04:54.258 --> 01:04:56.858
Watch it! Good!
Looks good!

01:04:56.860 --> 01:04:59.562
Toss me that torque wrench!

01:05:13.676 --> 01:05:15.877
Tommy, keep the water coming!

01:05:15.879 --> 01:05:17.179
Keep the water coming!

01:05:17.181 --> 01:05:19.181
I am!

01:05:21.051 --> 01:05:23.417
- Hey! Turn it off!
- Whoa, whoa!

01:05:23.419 --> 01:05:24.919
Shut it down! Shut it down!

01:05:27.223 --> 01:05:29.590
Hey! Hey!
Stop it! Stop it!

01:05:29.592 --> 01:05:30.558
All right!

01:05:30.560 --> 01:05:31.792
Back up, come on!

01:05:31.794 --> 01:05:33.728
- Shit!
- Ray! What happened?

01:05:33.730 --> 01:05:34.997
It's the rock.

01:05:34.999 --> 01:05:37.332
- Broke the drill bit.
- How did that happen?

01:05:37.334 --> 01:05:39.533
Sounds like a dyke
probably hit a vein.

01:05:39.535 --> 01:05:40.835
We need a carbide head.

01:05:40.837 --> 01:05:42.236
We have to get it from Norway.

01:05:42.238 --> 01:05:43.871
- It'll cost 60 grand.
- You got it.

01:05:43.873 --> 01:05:46.375
It's gonna take us way
longer to do this.

01:05:46.377 --> 01:05:47.808
Whatever it is,
you have to find

01:05:47.810 --> 01:05:49.076
a way through
that mountain.

01:05:49.078 --> 01:05:51.779
Don't tell me that it'll cost
more, because I have no more.

01:05:51.781 --> 01:05:53.781
Take it easy!
I couldn't predict this.

01:05:53.783 --> 01:05:56.183
This is part of the game!
It's full of surprises.

01:05:56.185 --> 01:05:58.451
Read your contract.
Surprises are on your side.

01:05:58.453 --> 01:06:00.054
- That's bullshit!
- Calm down!

01:06:00.056 --> 01:06:01.355
I don't know what to say.

01:06:01.357 --> 01:06:02.924
It's on paper.
You're responsible.

01:06:02.926 --> 01:06:05.026
We're busting our asses!
I don't need this!

01:06:05.028 --> 01:06:07.762
What happened? Why didn't they
use the carbide to begin with?

01:06:07.764 --> 01:06:08.763
Don't get
in his face!

01:06:08.765 --> 01:06:10.431
I thought you were
ahead of the game!

01:06:10.433 --> 01:06:11.899
We are!
We hit a vein!

01:06:11.901 --> 01:06:13.900
These things happen.
Relax! We'll solve it.

01:06:13.902 --> 01:06:15.568
Stop telling me that.
I'm relaxed.

01:06:15.570 --> 01:06:17.671
Not with the money
I'm paying. Where's Anton?

01:06:17.673 --> 01:06:18.873
Anton's up there.
Get some rest.

01:06:18.875 --> 01:06:20.440
What are you doing up there?

01:06:20.442 --> 01:06:21.909
Come on!
Let's go! Let's go!

01:06:21.911 --> 01:06:24.547
- Just get some rest, OK?
- All right.

01:06:26.182 --> 01:06:28.581
- I'm serious!
- You too.

01:06:28.583 --> 01:06:30.951
<i>Uh, there have been
a couple of delays.</i>

01:06:30.953 --> 01:06:32.452
The drilling in the mountain

01:06:32.454 --> 01:06:34.487
has been a pain in
the ass, literally.

01:06:34.489 --> 01:06:35.689
Does that change
our calendar?

01:06:35.691 --> 01:06:38.225
Are we still gonna be able
to use the line next month?

01:06:38.227 --> 01:06:41.130
At this point,
I'm... I'm not sure about that.

01:06:43.333 --> 01:06:45.932
You know, sometimes
I wonder, Vinnie.

01:06:45.934 --> 01:06:48.835
Do you really know
what you're doing?

01:06:50.406 --> 01:06:53.807
I mean, you asked us to invest
in this crazy project of yours,

01:06:53.809 --> 01:06:57.211
and then it's been nothing but
surprises since the beginning.

01:06:57.213 --> 01:06:59.714
No, there hasn't.
There's been one surprise.

01:06:59.716 --> 01:07:02.182
I think you might be
in over your head.

01:07:02.184 --> 01:07:04.418
I think we might be
in over our heads.

01:07:04.420 --> 01:07:06.519
Jesus! Bryan,
I'm on top of everything.

01:07:06.521 --> 01:07:09.656
It's just been a little harder
in that one spot, that's all.

01:07:09.658 --> 01:07:11.359
It's a lot of money
we're about to send you.

01:07:11.361 --> 01:07:13.160
Yeah, thank you, Mr. Simon.
I know that.

01:07:13.162 --> 01:07:15.729
Are you being
100% honest with us?

01:07:17.199 --> 01:07:19.966
All right, like,
I'm not gonna bullshit you, OK?

01:07:19.968 --> 01:07:22.135
The line might not be
100% operational

01:07:22.137 --> 01:07:23.503
in the next month, OK?

01:07:23.505 --> 01:07:26.673
But I think that once we can
prove our line is the fastest,

01:07:26.675 --> 01:07:29.310
the amount of money that people
will be willing to spend

01:07:29.312 --> 01:07:30.777
to get access to our line

01:07:30.779 --> 01:07:33.179
will skyrocket to the
stratosphere in a microsecond.

01:07:33.181 --> 01:07:35.015
Personally, I wanna
be there when it happens.

01:07:35.017 --> 01:07:37.516
But I can't go forward without
the next payment, all right?

01:07:37.518 --> 01:07:40.020
I got a drill that
costs $80,000 a day.

01:07:40.022 --> 01:07:41.454
I got a fucking Sikorsky
that's 70 feet long

01:07:41.456 --> 01:07:43.289
hovering above a
cliff in Pennsylvania.

01:07:43.291 --> 01:07:44.358
- One question.
- What?

01:07:44.360 --> 01:07:46.494
Are we getting
our money's worth?

01:07:46.496 --> 01:07:48.161
Or are you trying to screw us

01:07:48.163 --> 01:07:50.863
and give yourself
a big departure bonus

01:07:50.865 --> 01:07:52.698
when the shit hits the fan?

01:07:52.700 --> 01:07:53.832
Jesus, Bryan!

01:07:53.834 --> 01:07:55.667
You think I buried
500 miles of fiber

01:07:55.669 --> 01:07:56.535
from Kansas to Indianapolis

01:07:56.537 --> 01:07:58.705
as, what, a favor
to the Earth, OK?

01:08:00.175 --> 01:08:02.675
The line is halfway done.
It's more that halfway done.

01:08:02.677 --> 01:08:04.543
The line is gonna
be very fucking fast,

01:08:04.545 --> 01:08:06.279
and you're gonna be
very fucking rich, OK?

01:08:06.281 --> 01:08:07.982
I promise.
No asshole bonuses.

01:08:09.884 --> 01:08:12.485
Don't fuck us, Vinnie.
I trust you.

01:08:13.754 --> 01:08:16.022
I didn't spend the last
2 years doing this

01:08:16.024 --> 01:08:17.390
so I can just walk away!

01:08:17.392 --> 01:08:19.559
I'm doing this as if
it were the last thing

01:08:19.560 --> 01:08:21.260
that I do in my life, OK?

01:08:21.261 --> 01:08:24.865
But I... I cannot go forward
without the next payment.

01:08:28.537 --> 01:08:31.738
All right, Vinnie.
All right.

01:08:36.310 --> 01:08:38.176
What's the amount?

01:08:39.647 --> 01:08:42.216
$15,500,000.

01:08:45.786 --> 01:08:47.854
Check it!

01:08:59.233 --> 01:09:00.901
Thank you.

01:09:26.393 --> 01:09:27.692
Hi!

01:09:27.694 --> 01:09:29.060
Hi!

01:09:29.063 --> 01:09:30.564
How can I help you?

01:09:32.665 --> 01:09:37.169
Yeah, I just wanted to know
are all of your services legit?

01:09:37.171 --> 01:09:38.537
Yeah, of course.

01:09:38.540 --> 01:09:40.506
So this is all, like, legal.

01:09:40.508 --> 01:09:42.407
I could just get
a normal massage?

01:09:42.408 --> 01:09:43.509
Yes, sir.

01:09:43.511 --> 01:09:46.411
Would you like
a therapeutic massage

01:09:46.412 --> 01:09:48.080
or a relaxation massage?

01:09:48.082 --> 01:09:50.314
Um, therapeutic.

01:09:50.317 --> 01:09:52.151
Thirty minutes
or an hour?

01:09:52.153 --> 01:09:53.888
Thirty.

01:10:58.751 --> 01:10:59.916
Oh shit!

01:10:59.918 --> 01:11:02.252
<i>Where the hell are you, man?</i>

01:11:02.254 --> 01:11:04.854
I'm in the car on my way
back to the hotel. What's up?

01:11:04.856 --> 01:11:06.856
<i>There's land that
does not belong to us.</i>

01:11:06.858 --> 01:11:09.759
- Wait, what?
- <i>We're digging on the lot, a chunk of the land...</i>

01:11:09.761 --> 01:11:12.230
I thought we had the papers.
You said it was clear.

01:11:12.232 --> 01:11:14.332
<i>The railroad guy
said they don't own it.</i>

01:11:14.334 --> 01:11:15.966
- Who?
- <i>You need to get here now...</i>

01:11:15.968 --> 01:11:18.569
Yeah, whatever, I'll meet you
there in the morning.

01:11:18.571 --> 01:11:20.036
- <i>Hurry up, please.</i>
- Yeah.

01:11:20.038 --> 01:11:21.407
Fuck!

01:11:38.023 --> 01:11:40.123
Stupid millisecond!

01:11:40.125 --> 01:11:41.594
Think you can beat me?

01:11:42.595 --> 01:11:44.161
Yeah! I'm gonna beat you.

01:11:44.163 --> 01:11:46.163
Beat you!
That's what you get.

01:11:46.165 --> 01:11:48.367
That's what you get,
motherfucker!

01:12:23.502 --> 01:12:25.000
Hello?

01:12:25.002 --> 01:12:26.802
<i>Oh, good, you're alive!</i>

01:12:26.804 --> 01:12:27.803
Oh! Hi!

01:12:27.805 --> 01:12:29.205
<i>Why haven't you called?</i>

01:12:29.207 --> 01:12:30.573
<i>It's been a week, Anton.</i>

01:12:30.575 --> 01:12:32.108
<i>Tell me what's wrong.</i>

01:12:32.110 --> 01:12:33.143
Nothing!

01:12:34.546 --> 01:12:35.978
<i>This line's hurting you.</i>

01:12:35.980 --> 01:12:38.381
<i>Don't you see
that it's hurting you?</i>

01:12:38.383 --> 01:12:41.785
<i>Why does Vinnie still need you
to be there?</i>

01:12:41.787 --> 01:12:44.487
<i>Look, the kids miss you.
I miss you.</i>

01:12:44.489 --> 01:12:45.722
I gotta go.

01:12:45.724 --> 01:12:47.590
<i>Why can't you just
work from here?</i>

01:12:47.592 --> 01:12:49.592
I gotta go.
I'll call you right back.

01:12:49.594 --> 01:12:50.593
- <i>Babe?</i>
- I'm sorry.

01:12:50.595 --> 01:12:52.029
<i>Anton! Anton!</i>

01:13:20.157 --> 01:13:21.890
Good! Good! Good!

01:13:21.892 --> 01:13:24.226
- What's up, Vinnie?
- Yo!

01:13:24.228 --> 01:13:26.897
You know what?
Wait for me here.

01:13:31.035 --> 01:13:33.202
Wonderful! Well played!

01:13:34.806 --> 01:13:37.072
Hi! Good afternoon!
Hello!

01:13:37.074 --> 01:13:38.475
Good day to you, sir.

01:13:38.477 --> 01:13:39.575
Are you with that man?

01:13:39.577 --> 01:13:41.075
Uh, yes,
that's my partner.

01:13:41.077 --> 01:13:44.213
My name is Vincent Zaleski.
I work for Cobalt Fiber Tech.

01:13:44.215 --> 01:13:47.383
We were wondering if you were
the owner of this property.

01:13:47.385 --> 01:13:50.018
Yes, we all are. We already
talked to your partner.

01:13:50.020 --> 01:13:52.722
Right, and first of all,
I should apologize,

01:13:52.724 --> 01:13:54.456
because I wasn't there,
but I suspect

01:13:54.458 --> 01:13:57.058
he may have been a little
rude when he approached you.

01:13:57.060 --> 01:13:59.762
Yeah, so, we want to expand
our operations to this area

01:13:59.764 --> 01:14:01.129
and bring in all
sorts of new

01:14:01.131 --> 01:14:03.399
and exciting opportunities
to this community.

01:14:03.401 --> 01:14:05.701
We'd like to bring in a
high-speed fiber network.

01:14:05.703 --> 01:14:08.270
We'd like to could buy a
very narrow strip of land,

01:14:08.272 --> 01:14:09.706
not more than
one foot wide.

01:14:09.708 --> 01:14:12.006
We'd come in for a week
or two and install it.

01:14:12.008 --> 01:14:14.610
We'd hide our tube
underground and leave.

01:14:14.612 --> 01:14:16.378
It wouldn't leave a trace,

01:14:16.380 --> 01:14:18.280
and we'd compensate
you for your troubles.

01:14:18.282 --> 01:14:19.882
We're not interested,
thank you.

01:14:19.884 --> 01:14:21.617
But I'm sure our
neighbors will be.

01:14:21.619 --> 01:14:23.118
You should go
and talk to them.

01:14:23.120 --> 01:14:24.553
- Mm-hmm.
- Sorry.

01:14:24.555 --> 01:14:27.922
We would be willing to
offer you $230,000

01:14:27.924 --> 01:14:29.691
for this right of way.

01:14:34.799 --> 01:14:36.365
$230,000 is
a lot of money.

01:14:36.367 --> 01:14:39.000
I'm sure our neighbors
will be very interested.

01:14:39.002 --> 01:14:40.968
Was that all you
came to talk about?

01:14:40.970 --> 01:14:44.439
Sir, I just want to make sure
that you completely understand.

01:14:44.441 --> 01:14:46.974
This line would be hidden
6 feet underground.

01:14:46.976 --> 01:14:48.409
No one would ever see it.

01:14:48.411 --> 01:14:51.212
We would come in, we would
take 2 weeks to install it,

01:14:51.214 --> 01:14:53.247
and leave you with
a check for $230,000.

01:14:53.249 --> 01:14:54.850
That much money
can go a long way

01:14:54.852 --> 01:14:57.018
to preserving your
heritage, your traditions.

01:14:57.020 --> 01:14:59.020
That's exactly
what I understood,

01:14:59.022 --> 01:15:00.888
and I said we're
not interested.

01:15:00.890 --> 01:15:02.557
We live simple
lives, Mr. Zaleski,

01:15:02.559 --> 01:15:03.925
at the service of God.

01:15:03.927 --> 01:15:05.560
High speed is not
our priority,

01:15:05.562 --> 01:15:07.562
and money can be
a source of conflict.

01:15:07.564 --> 01:15:09.397
Right, well,
do you think maybe

01:15:09.399 --> 01:15:11.299
you could do a
group vote on this?

01:15:11.301 --> 01:15:13.968
Please don't make
this difficult.

01:15:13.970 --> 01:15:15.937
Look, sir,
all I'm trying to do

01:15:15.939 --> 01:15:18.773
is to help bring prosperity
to this community,

01:15:18.775 --> 01:15:20.608
to make things better for you.

01:15:20.610 --> 01:15:21.809
We don't believe that

01:15:21.811 --> 01:15:23.678
making things faster
makes things better.

01:15:23.680 --> 01:15:24.913
Mm-hmm.

01:15:24.915 --> 01:15:27.281
We believe that all
this new technology

01:15:27.283 --> 01:15:29.250
makes us more
distant and isolated.

01:15:29.252 --> 01:15:31.518
That's why we do not
want to have

01:15:31.520 --> 01:15:34.122
your high-speed tube
under our land.

01:15:35.157 --> 01:15:36.858
So, what do we do now?

01:15:36.860 --> 01:15:38.860
I don't understand.

01:15:38.862 --> 01:15:40.761
How do we find
common ground?

01:15:40.763 --> 01:15:42.163
We don't, Mr. Zaleski.

01:15:42.165 --> 01:15:44.098
We will never
find common ground.

01:15:44.100 --> 01:15:45.700
This is the
Lord's ground.

01:15:45.702 --> 01:15:47.567
There's nothing
common about it.

01:15:47.569 --> 01:15:50.337
We are here to take care
of it at his service.

01:15:50.339 --> 01:15:51.639
Mm-hmm.

01:15:51.641 --> 01:15:53.340
I'm sorry.
You have a nice day.

01:15:53.342 --> 01:15:55.576
- Don't be stupid, sir.
- Vincent, come on.

01:15:55.578 --> 01:15:56.978
- We're done.
- I'm sorry.

01:15:56.980 --> 01:15:59.480
You're making a very
big mistake. Have a good day!

01:15:59.482 --> 01:16:00.982
All right. Thank you!

01:16:00.984 --> 01:16:02.717
I think I have
an idea, Vincent.

01:16:13.563 --> 01:16:16.964
<i>A historical
landmark was made yesterday</i>

01:16:16.966 --> 01:16:20.333
<i>when an Austrian skydiver broke
the supersonic barrier</i>

01:16:20.335 --> 01:16:22.369
<i>as he dived 39 km
to the ground...</i>

01:16:24.172 --> 01:16:27.274
<i>...landing safely in the
southwest of the United States.</i>

01:16:27.276 --> 01:16:29.810
<i>His pathway through
the Earth's atmosphere</i>

01:16:29.812 --> 01:16:31.278
<i>took 7 years to plan...</i>

01:16:32.649 --> 01:16:34.147
<i>Early in the morning,</i>

01:16:34.149 --> 01:16:37.182
<i>the man patiently went up
